\chapter{Households}
\label{chap:households}
%#############################################################


Households are sites of energy and material consumption.
For example, Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_sankey} shows that 
11.5~quads of energy are consumed in U.S.\ residences%
\footnote{
A quad is 1 short quadrillion BTUs, or $10^{15}$~BTU.
},
%
predominantly electricity, natural gas, and petroleum.
This 11.5~quads represents 16\% of final energy consumption.
Energy consumption is the source of sustainability impacts
(CO$_2$ emissions and resource depletion, for example)
far beyond the site (e.g., households)
where useable energy is converted to heat.
In addition to energy, sustainability impacts arise 
from household decisions about food and material consumption, too.
Thus, decisions made in households have sustainability implications
far beyond the walls of each abode.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\figwidth]{chapters/ch07-Households/figures/Energy_US_2020.png}
\caption{U.S.\ energy consumption 2020.}
\label{fig:LLNL_sankey}
\end{figure}

Some people (physical plant employees, custodial staff, or supervisors)
control buildings and appliances
that consume energy, material, and other resources.
Such leaders make decisions every day that have sustainability implications.
``Regular'' people often have little power to make decisions
with sustainability implications
in many areas of life 
(work, school, or church).
However, many everyday people made decisions with sustainability implications
in their own household.

